--------------------------------------------------
https://wiki.cdot.senecacollege.ca/wiki/AArch64_Register_and_Instruction_Quick_Start
--------------------------------------------------

ARCHITECTURE: arm aarch64
INSTRUCTION: ALL

add r0,r1,r2      // load r0 with r1+r2
add r0,r1,99      // load r0 with r1+99
adr r0,label      // load r0 with the address label (this actually calculates an address from the PC plus an offset)
bl label          // branch (with link) to label - this is a procedure / subroutine / function call
br label          // branch to label - this is a goto
br register       // branch to the address in register
b.eq label        // branch to label if equal
b.ne label        // branch to label if not equal
b.lt label        // branch to label if less
b.gt label        // branch to label if greater
cmp r0,r1         // compare register r0 with register r1. The comparison sets flags in the processor status register which affect conditional branches.
cmp r0,99         // compare the number 99 with register r0. The comparison sets flags in the processor status register which affect conditional branches.
ldr r0,[r1,0]     // load register r0 from the address pointed to by (r1 + (0 * size)) where size is 8 bytes for 64-bit stores, 4 bytes for 32-bit stores
ldr w0,[r1,0]     // like above but reads 32 bits only - note the use of w0 instead of r0 for the source register name
ldrb w0,[r1,0]    // like above but reads 1 byte (8 bits) only - note the use of w0 for the source register name
ldur r0,[r1,0]    // load register r0 from the address pointed to by (r1 + 0) - the mnemonic means "load unscaled register"
mov r0,r1         // move data from r1 to r0
mov r0,99         // load r0 with 99 (only certain immediate values are possible)
ret               // return from subroutine (counterpart to bl)
str r0,[r1,0]     // store register r0 to address pointed to by (r1 + (0 * size)) where size is 8 bytes for 64-bit stores
strb w0,[r1,0]    // like str but writes one byte only - note the use of w0 for the source register name
stur r0,[r1,0]    // store register r0 to the address pointed to by (r1 + 0) - the mnemonic means "store unscaled register"
svc 0             // perform a syscall
msub r0,r1,r2,r3  // load r0 with r3-(r1*r2) (useful for calculating remainders)
madd r0,r1,r2,r3  // load r0 with r3+(r1*r2)
mul r0,r1,r2      // load r0 with r1*r2 (actually an alias - see ARM ARM)
push r0           // push r0 onto the stack
pop r0            // pop r0 off the stack
udiv r0,r1,r2     // unsigned - divide r1 by r2, places quotient into r0 - remainder is not calculated (use msub)


END_INSTRUCTION: ALL

INSTRUCTION: STP LDP
** Load pair (LDP) and store pair (STP) **

These pair instructions transfer two registers to and from memory. The first instruction loads [X0] into W3, and loads [X0 + 4] into W7:

LDP        W3, W7, [X0]

This second instruction stores D0 into [X4] and stores D1 to [X4 + 8]:

STP        D0, D1, [X4]            

Load and store pair instructions are often used for pushing, and popping off the stack. This first instruction pushes X0 and X1 onto the stack:

STP        X0, X1, [SP, #-16]!

This second instruction pops X0 and X1 from the stack:

LDP        X0, X1, [SP], #16
Remember that in AArch64 the stack-pointer must be 128-bit aligned.

* Note: It is from https://developer.arm.com/documentation/102374/0101/Loads-and-stores---load-pair-and-store-pair

END_INSTRUCTION: STP LDP



# ----------------------------------------------------------------
# AArch64 / ARM64 instruction reference (common in kernel disasm).
# Semantics from the Arm Architecture Reference Manual (Arm ARM).
# ----------------------------------------------------------------

INSTRUCTION: mov movz movk movn
Move a register, or build a wide immediate.

  mov  Xd, Xn/Wn         - copy a register (alias of ORR Xd, XZR, Xn)
  mov  Xd, #imm          - load an immediate (assembler picks the form)
  movz Xd, #imm{, LSL #s}- move wide with Zero: put a 16-bit immediate in
                           one halfword (s = 0/16/32/48) and zero the rest
  movk Xd, #imm{, LSL #s}- move wide with Keep: put a 16-bit immediate in
                           one halfword, leaving the other bits unchanged
  movn Xd, #imm{, LSL #s}- move wide with NOT: like movz but stores ~value

Note
  A 64-bit constant is built with one MOVZ and up to three MOVK, e.g.
    movz x0, #0x1234
    movk x0, #0x5678, lsl #16
  Wn is the 32-bit view of a register, Xn the 64-bit view.
END_INSTRUCTION: mov movz movk movn

INSTRUCTION: mvn
Bitwise NOT: Xd = ~(shifted Xm). Alias of ORN Xd, XZR, Xm.
END_INSTRUCTION: mvn

INSTRUCTION: add adds
Add. ADDS also updates the NZCV condition flags.

  add Xd, Xn, Xm{, shift}        - Xd = Xn + shifted(Xm)
  add Xd, Xn, #imm{, LSL #12}    - Xd = Xn + imm (12-bit, optional <<12)
  add Xd, Xn, Wm, {sxtw|uxtw} #s - extended-register form used for array
                                   indexing (extend Wm, shift, then add)

CMN is an alias of ADDS with the result discarded.
END_INSTRUCTION: add adds

INSTRUCTION: sub subs
Subtract. SUBS also updates the NZCV condition flags.

  sub Xd, Xn, Xm{, shift}
  sub Xd, Xn, #imm{, LSL #12}

CMP is an alias of SUBS with the result discarded; NEG/NEGS are aliases
of SUB/SUBS from XZR.
END_INSTRUCTION: sub subs

INSTRUCTION: neg negs
Negate: Xd = -(shifted Xm). Alias of SUB Xd, XZR, Xm; NEGS also sets
the NZCV flags.
END_INSTRUCTION: neg negs

INSTRUCTION: cmp cmn
Compare, setting the NZCV flags for a following conditional branch or
select. The result is discarded.

  cmp Xn, Xm/#imm  - flags from (Xn - operand); alias of SUBS XZR, ...
  cmn Xn, Xm/#imm  - flags from (Xn + operand); alias of ADDS XZR, ...
END_INSTRUCTION: cmp cmn

INSTRUCTION: tst
Test bits: set the N and Z flags from (Xn AND operand), discarding the
result. Alias of ANDS XZR, Xn, operand. Commonly precedes b.eq / b.ne.
END_INSTRUCTION: tst

INSTRUCTION: and ands
Bitwise AND. ANDS also updates the N and Z flags (TST is ANDS with the
result discarded).
END_INSTRUCTION: and ands

INSTRUCTION: orr orn
Bitwise OR / OR-NOT (orn ORs with the inverted operand). MOV (register)
is an alias of ORR Xd, XZR, Xm.
END_INSTRUCTION: orr orn

INSTRUCTION: eor eon
Bitwise exclusive-OR / exclusive-OR-NOT (eon XORs with the inverted
operand).
END_INSTRUCTION: eor eon

INSTRUCTION: bic bics
Bit clear: Xd = Xn AND NOT(shifted Xm). BICS also updates the N and Z
flags.
END_INSTRUCTION: bic bics

INSTRUCTION: lsl lsr asr ror
Shift and rotate (register or immediate forms).

  lsl - logical shift left   (fills with zeros)
  lsr - logical shift right  (fills with zeros)
  asr - arithmetic shift right (sign-preserving)
  ror - rotate right

The immediate forms are assembler aliases of the bitfield moves
UBFM/SBFM (and EXTR for ROR).
END_INSTRUCTION: lsl lsr asr ror

INSTRUCTION: mul madd msub mneg
Multiply (low 64/32 bits of the product).

  mul  Xd, Xn, Xm      - Xd = Xn * Xm          (alias of MADD ...,XZR)
  madd Xd, Xn, Xm, Xa  - Xd = Xa + (Xn * Xm)
  msub Xd, Xn, Xm, Xa  - Xd = Xa - (Xn * Xm)   (used to get a remainder)
  mneg Xd, Xn, Xm      - Xd = -(Xn * Xm)       (alias of MSUB ...,XZR)
END_INSTRUCTION: mul madd msub mneg

INSTRUCTION: smull umull smulh umulh smaddl umaddl
Long / high multiply.

  smull/umull Xd, Wn, Wm    - signed/unsigned 32x32 -> 64-bit product
  smulh/umulh Xd, Xn, Xm    - high 64 bits of a signed/unsigned 64x64
  smaddl/umaddl Xd,Wn,Wm,Xa - Xd = Xa + (Wn * Wm) widened to 64 bits
END_INSTRUCTION: smull umull smulh umulh smaddl umaddl

INSTRUCTION: sdiv udiv
Signed / unsigned divide: Xd = Xn / Xm, truncated toward zero. There is
no remainder register; compute it with  msub Xrem, Xquot, Xm, Xn.
Division by zero produces 0 and does not trap.
END_INSTRUCTION: sdiv udiv

INSTRUCTION: sxtb sxth sxtw uxtb uxth
Sign- or zero-extend a byte / halfword / word into a wider register
(aliases of SBFM/UBFM). E.g.  sxtw Xd, Wn  sign-extends a 32-bit value
to 64 bits; uxtb Wd, Wn keeps the low byte and zeros the rest.
END_INSTRUCTION: sxtb sxth sxtw uxtb uxth

INSTRUCTION: sbfx ubfx sbfiz ubfiz bfi bfxil
Bitfield operations (aliases of SBFM/UBFM/BFM).

  ubfx/sbfx  Xd, Xn, #lsb, #width - extract a zero/sign-extended field
  ubfiz/sbfiz Xd, Xn, #lsb, #width- extract, then shift left into zeros
  bfi   Xd, Xn, #lsb, #width - insert a field, other bits unchanged
  bfxil Xd, Xn, #lsb, #width - insert low bits, top bits unchanged
END_INSTRUCTION: sbfx ubfx sbfiz ubfiz bfi bfxil

INSTRUCTION: ldr ldrb ldrh ldrsb ldrsh ldrsw
Load a value from memory into a register.

  ldr   Xt/Wt, [addr] - load 8 bytes (Xt) or 4 bytes (Wt)
  ldrb  Wt, [addr]    - load 1 byte,  zero-extended
  ldrh  Wt, [addr]    - load 2 bytes, zero-extended
  ldrsb/ldrsh/ldrsw   - load 1/2/4 bytes, sign-extended into Xt

Addressing forms
  [Xn, #imm]          offset
  [Xn, #imm]!         pre-index  (update Xn, then access)
  [Xn], #imm          post-index (access, then update Xn)
  [Xn, Xm{, LSL #s}]  register offset (array indexing)
  ldr Xt, label       PC-relative literal load
END_INSTRUCTION: ldr ldrb ldrh ldrsb ldrsh ldrsw

INSTRUCTION: str strb strh
Store a register to memory; STRB/STRH store the low 1 / 2 bytes. Uses
the same addressing forms as LDR (offset, pre-/post-index, register
offset).
END_INSTRUCTION: str strb strh

INSTRUCTION: ldur stur ldurb sturb ldurh sturh
Load / store using an unscaled 9-bit signed byte offset: [Xn, #simm]
only, with no indexing. The assembler emits these when the offset is not
a scaled multiple of the access size.
END_INSTRUCTION: ldur stur ldurb sturb ldurh sturh

INSTRUCTION: ldar stlr ldapr
Load-acquire / store-release: ordered single-copy-atomic accesses used
to implement locks and smp_load_acquire() / smp_store_release().
LDAR orders later accesses after it; STLR orders earlier accesses before
it.
END_INSTRUCTION: ldar stlr ldapr

INSTRUCTION: ldxr stxr ldaxr stlxr ldxrb stxrb ldaxrb stlxrb
Exclusive load / store (load-linked / store-conditional) used to build
atomics and spinlocks.

  ldxr/ldaxr Xt, [Xn]     - load-exclusive (ldaxr also acquires)
  stxr/stlxr Ws, Xt, [Xn] - store-exclusive; Ws = 0 success, 1 fail

The code retries the sequence until the store succeeds. On CPUs with
LSE, the single-instruction atomics below replace this loop.
END_INSTRUCTION: ldxr stxr ldaxr stlxr ldxrb stxrb ldaxrb stlxrb

INSTRUCTION: cas casb cash casp ldadd ldset ldclr ldeor swp stadd
LSE atomics (ARMv8.1, single-instruction atomics):

  cas   - atomic compare-and-swap
  ldadd - atomic fetch-and-add        stadd - atomic add (no result)
  ldset - atomic fetch-and-OR
  ldclr - atomic fetch-and-bit-clear (AND NOT)
  ldeor - atomic fetch-and-XOR
  swp   - atomic swap

Suffixes: a / l / al add acquire / release ordering; b / h operate on a
byte / halfword. The kernel uses these for atomic_t and locks when the
CPU supports LSE.
END_INSTRUCTION: cas casb cash casp ldadd ldset ldclr ldeor swp stadd

INSTRUCTION: adr adrp
Form a PC-relative address.

  adr  Xd, label - Xd = PC + signed offset (+/-1 MB range)
  adrp Xd, label - Xd = (PC & ~0xfff) + (offset << 12): the 4 KB *page*
                   base, +/-4 GB range. Usually followed by
                   add Xd, Xd, #:lo12:label  to add the low 12 bits and
                   form the full address.
END_INSTRUCTION: adr adrp

INSTRUCTION: b br
Unconditional branch (goto).

  b  label - branch to a PC-relative label (+/-128 MB)
  br Xn    - branch to the address in Xn (jump tables, tail calls)
END_INSTRUCTION: b br

INSTRUCTION: bl blr
Branch with link (function call): the return address is saved in x30
(the link register, LR).

  bl  label - call a PC-relative target
  blr Xn    - call the address in Xn (indirect / function-pointer call)
END_INSTRUCTION: bl blr

INSTRUCTION: ret
Return from a function by branching to the address in the link register
(x30 by default, or the register named). Counterpart to BL/BLR.
END_INSTRUCTION: ret

INSTRUCTION: cbz cbnz
Compare with zero and branch, without changing the condition flags.

  cbz  Xn, label - branch if Xn == 0
  cbnz Xn, label - branch if Xn != 0
END_INSTRUCTION: cbz cbnz

INSTRUCTION: tbz tbnz
Test one bit and branch, without changing the condition flags.

  tbz  Xn, #bit, label - branch if that bit is 0
  tbnz Xn, #bit, label - branch if that bit is 1
END_INSTRUCTION: tbz tbnz

INSTRUCTION: b.eq b.ne b.cs b.hs b.cc b.lo b.mi b.pl b.vs b.vc b.hi b.ls b.ge b.lt b.gt b.le b.al
Conditional branch: taken when the NZCV flags (set by a prior
CMP/CMN/TST/SUBS/ADDS/CCMP) satisfy the condition.

  eq / ne        equal / not equal                 (Z)
  hs(cs) / lo(cc) unsigned >= / unsigned <          (C)
  hi / ls        unsigned > / unsigned <=
  ge / lt        signed >= / signed <
  gt / le        signed > / signed <=
  mi / pl        negative / non-negative           (N)
  vs / vc        overflow set / clear              (V)
  al             always
END_INSTRUCTION: b.eq b.ne b.cs b.hs b.cc b.lo b.mi b.pl b.vs b.vc b.hi b.ls b.ge b.lt b.gt b.le b.al

INSTRUCTION: csel cset csetm csinc csinv csneg cinc cinv cneg
Conditional select family: choose a value from the flags instead of
branching (branchless code).

  csel  Xd, Xn, Xm, cond - Xd = cond ? Xn : Xm
  cset  Xd, cond         - Xd = cond ? 1 : 0
  csetm Xd, cond         - Xd = cond ? ~0 : 0
  csinc/csinv/csneg      - when cond is false the second source becomes
                           Xm+1 / ~Xm / -Xm
  cinc/cinv/cneg         - single-source aliases of the above
END_INSTRUCTION: csel cset csetm csinc csinv csneg cinc cinv cneg

INSTRUCTION: ccmp ccmn
Conditional compare: if the current condition holds, compare and set
NZCV; otherwise load NZCV from the given #nzcv immediate. Used to build
compound conditions (a && b, a || b) without branches.
END_INSTRUCTION: ccmp ccmn

INSTRUCTION: nop
No operation (a HINT-space encoding). Used for alignment padding and for
patchable call sites - the kernel patches NOP <-> BL for ftrace and
static calls.
END_INSTRUCTION: nop

INSTRUCTION: mrs msr
Move to / from a system register.

  mrs Xt, <sysreg>        - read a system register (e.g. mrs x0, sp_el0)
  msr <sysreg>, Xt        - write a system register
  msr <pstatefield>, #imm - set a PSTATE field, e.g. msr daifset, #2 to
                            mask IRQs (DAIF bits D=8 A=4 I=2 F=1)
END_INSTRUCTION: mrs msr

INSTRUCTION: svc hvc smc
Synchronous exception-generating calls.

  svc #imm - supervisor call: user -> kernel (EL1) syscall entry
  hvc #imm - hypervisor call: -> EL2
  smc #imm - secure monitor call: -> EL3 firmware (PSCI, e.g. CPU on/off)
END_INSTRUCTION: svc hvc smc

INSTRUCTION: wfe wfi sev sevl yield
Low-power and spin-loop hints.

  wfe  - wait for event (spinlock waiters sleep here until an SEV)
  wfi  - wait for interrupt (used by cpu_do_idle)
  sev / sevl - signal an event to wake WFE waiters
  yield - hint that this is a spin-loop iteration
END_INSTRUCTION: wfe wfi sev sevl yield

INSTRUCTION: dmb dsb isb
Barriers.

  dmb <opt> - data memory barrier: order memory accesses (e.g. dmb ish)
  dsb <opt> - data synchronization barrier: order + wait for completion
  isb       - instruction sync barrier: flush the pipeline after changing
              system state

Common domains: ish (inner shareable), sy (full system), plus ld/st
variants such as ishld / ishst.
END_INSTRUCTION: dmb dsb isb

INSTRUCTION: eret
Exception return: restore PC from ELR_ELx and PSTATE from SPSR_ELx,
returning from an exception handler to the interrupted context.
END_INSTRUCTION: eret

INSTRUCTION: brk hlt
Software breakpoint / halt. AArch64 BUG(), WARN() and kprobes are built
on BRK #imm, which raises a synchronous debug exception; the kernel
decodes the reason from the immediate.
END_INSTRUCTION: brk hlt

INSTRUCTION: clz cls rbit rev rev16 rev32
Bit / byte manipulation.

  clz  - count leading zeros
  cls  - count leading sign bits
  rbit - reverse the bit order
  rev  - byte-reverse a whole register (endianness swap)
  rev16/rev32 - byte-reverse within each 16- / 32-bit element
END_INSTRUCTION: clz cls rbit rev rev16 rev32

INSTRUCTION: extr
Extract: read a register-width field spanning a pair of registers at a
bit offset, Xd = (Xn:Xm) >> #lsb. ROR is the special case Xn == Xm.
END_INSTRUCTION: extr

INSTRUCTION: paciasp pacibsp autiasp autibsp pacia pacib autia autib xpaclri
Pointer Authentication (ARMv8.3, CONFIG_ARM64_PTR_AUTH). Signs and
authenticates return addresses to defend against ROP.

  paciasp - sign LR (x30) using SP as context (function prologue)
  autiasp - authenticate LR before RET (epilogue); a tampered LR faults
            when it is used
  xpaclri - strip the PAC bits from LR (used when unwinding / printing)

These live in the HINT space, so they execute as NOPs on CPUs without
pointer authentication.
END_INSTRUCTION: paciasp pacibsp autiasp autibsp pacia pacib autia autib xpaclri

INSTRUCTION: bti
Branch Target Identification (ARMv8.5, CONFIG_ARM64_BTI): a landing pad
at a legal indirect-branch target. An indirect branch to a location
without a matching BTI / PACIASP raises a Branch Target exception.
Encoded in the HINT space, so it is a NOP on older CPUs.
END_INSTRUCTION: bti

INSTRUCTION: hint
Hint instruction: the encoding space behind NOP, YIELD, WFE/WFI, SEV and
the pointer-auth / BTI mnemonics. An unrecognized hint executes as a
NOP.
END_INSTRUCTION: hint

END_ARCHITECTURE: arm aarch64
